Firstly, you will need to define your uncertain nonlinear system. Let's consider a simple example for illustration purposes:

```
% Uncertain nonlinear system:
% x_dot = f(x) + g(x)*u

f = @(x) [x(2); -x(1) - x(2)^2];
g = @(x) [0; 1];
```

Next, implement actuator and sensor faults. You can model them as some functions of time, states, or inputs. For example:

```
% Actuator fault: fa(t,x,u)
% Sensor fault: fs(t,x)

fa = @(t, x, u) 0.1 * sin(t);
fs = @(t, x) 0.05 * x;
```

Now, add the DoS attack modeling. You can represent it as a binary function.

```
% DoS attack: dos(t)
% 1: under attack, 0: normal operation

dos = @(t) 1 - double(t < 10 || (t > 20 && t < 30));
```

To implement a high dynamic observer, you can use a sliding mode observer (SMO). Firstly, define the observer dynamics and design parameters:

```
% Sliding mode observer (SMO)
% x_hat_dot = f(x_hat) + g(x_hat)*u + L*(y_hat - y)

eta = 1;
L = [1, 1];
```

Now, simulate everything using MATLAB's `ode45` to solve the system of ODEs:

``` matlab
% Time horizon
Tspan = [0, 40];

% Initial conditions (system and observer)
x0 = [1; 0];
x_hat0 = [2; 0];

% Reference tracking
xr = @(t) sin(t);

% Solve ODEs
options = odeset('RelTol', 1e-3, 'AbsTol', 1e-6);
[t, x] = ode45(@(t, x) system_ode(t, x, f, g, fa, fs, dos, eta, L, xr), Tspan, [x0; x_hat0], options);

% Extract system states and observer estimates
x = x(:, 1:2);
x_hat = x(:, 3:4);
```

The performance of the observer and the impact of the actuator/sensor faults and the DoS attack can be analyzed by comparing the system states `x` and the estimated states `x_hat`.

